ueer Latinidad, Rodríguez shows how Latinx culture helped shape British post-punk. He traces the fandom networks that link these groups across space and time to illuminate how popular music establishes and facilitates intimate relations across the Atlantic. In so doing, he demonstrates how the music and styles that have come to define the 1980s hold significant sway over younger generations equally enthused by their matchlessly pleasurable and political reverberations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHispanic American gaysxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aHispanic American youthxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPopular musiczGreat BritainxLatin American influences. 0aPost-punk musicvCross-cultural studies. 0aYouthzGreat BritainxSocial life and customsy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023180?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023180/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles